data.content:
## Thread.Abort Migration Analysis

**Inventory found 3 APIs to migrate:**

| API | Location | Pattern |
|-----|----------|---------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `Stop()` | Cancellable work loop |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `ProcessLoop()` | Control flow + cleanup |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `ProcessLoop()` | Continue execution after abort |

### Why this breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` â€” the runtime no longer supports forcible thread termination. You must switch to **cooperative cancellation** via `CancellationToken`.

### Key pitfalls in this specific code

1. **`GetNextItem()` may block** â€” if it blocks indefinitely, cancellation never fires unless you pass the token into that call. This is the #1 mistake in these migrations.
2. **`ResetAbort()` lets the loop continue** â€” the intent is "roll back this item, then keep processing." With cooperative cancellation, you check `IsCancellationRequested` instead of re-entering the loop blindly.
3. **`Thread.Sleep(2000)` is a crude grace period** â€” replace with `Thread.Join(timeout)` which actually waits for the thread to finish.
4. **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** â€” it's `IDisposable`; leaking it leaks timers.

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // CRITICAL: pass the token into blocking calls,
                // otherwise cancellation stalls here until the
                // call returns on its own.
                var item = GetNextItem(token);
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Replaces catch (ThreadAbortException).
                // Clean up partial work, same as before.
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed â€” cooperative cancellation
                // doesn't force-rethrow. The loop condition will
                // exit naturally on the next iteration.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerThread is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signals the token â€” replaces Thread.Abort()

        // Wait up to 2 seconds for graceful exit (replaces Thread.Sleep)
        if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
        {
            // Thread didn't stop in time. With cooperative cancellation,
            // you CANNOT force-kill it. If this happens, it means
            // GetNextItem or ProcessItem isn't honoring the token.
            // Log a warning â€” this is a bug to fix, not to paper over.
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### What changed and why

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationTokenSource` + `CancellationToken` | Token integrates with blocking APIs (`WaitHandle`, async I/O); a bool cannot interrupt a blocked thread |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Cooperative signal instead of forcible exception injection |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` | The `when` guard avoids catching unrelated OCEs from other sources |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | *(removed)* | No forced rethrow to suppress â€” `OperationCanceledException` is a normal exception |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` | `_workerThread.Join(2000)` | Actually waits for the thread instead of sleeping blindly |

### You must also update `GetNextItem`

This is the **most critical part**. If `GetNextItem` blocks (e.g., on a queue or I/O), it must accept and honor the token:

```csharp
// Before â€” blocks indefinitely, immune to cancellation
private WorkItem GetNextItem() {
    return _queue.Take(); // BlockingCollection.Take()
}

// After â€” wakes up when cancelled
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token) {
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException
}
```

If `GetNextItem` calls something that doesn't accept a token (e.g., synchronous socket read), replace it with an async alternative or use `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne()` to make the blocking call cancellation-aware.

### Validation checklist

- âś… No `Thread.Abort`, `ThreadAbortException`, or `ResetAbort` references
- âś… `CancellationToken` passed through the full call chain
- âś… `CancellationTokenSource` is disposed via `IDisposable`
- âś… Blocking call (`GetNextItem`) accepts and honors the token
- âś… Builds cleanly on `net8.0` with no `SYSLIB0006` warnings
